@node "intro"

The  @{b}Amiga  500@{ub}  brought the world of assembly programming to European
teenagers who really should have stuck to playing games, and hence was born the
(incompatible) [mega]demo.

@{b}DPaint@{ub}  brought  the  power  of  graphics  to  programmers  who really
shouldn't draw.

@{b}ProTracker@{ub}  brought  the power of the sound sameple to programmers who
unfortunately fancied themselves musicians and hence was born:  the techno mod.

And now, PWS proudly presents....

@{i}==---A-P-E-R-C-K-E-Y--->@{ui}

@{b}APercKey@{ub} brings the power of the drumkit to programmers (and lamerz
alike).

After  installation,  your entire keypad will be turned into a virtual drumkit.
Just  turn  the  volume  up to 11 on your amp and load your CD player with some
@{"recommended listening material" link "music"}, and let your "Fingers Do The Drumming" (TM)

@endnode

@node "install"
You will need a lot of samples to begin with: preferably one for each key on
the keypad, to make the most of the program.
To install the program, you will need to place a text config file in s: 
called "samples".

Each line in the config file refers to an assignment to a key on the keypad
The first line refers to the first key, (see below). There are 18 lines in
the file. Below is a representation of the keypad, and the associated line
number in s:samples..
 __   __   __   __
|15| |16| |17| |18|
|__| |__| |__| |__|
 __   __   __   __
|11| |12| |13| |14|
|__| |__| |__| |__|
 __   __   __   __
| 7| | 8| | 9| |10|
|__| |__| |__| |__|
 __   __   __   __
| 4| | 5| | 6| | 3|
|__| |__| |__| |  |
 _______   __  |  |
|      1| | 2| |  |
|_______| |__| |__|

Each line has the format:

@{b}filename,channel,frequency@{ub}

where @{b}channel@{ub} is 0-3 and @{b}frequency@{ub} is 0-22000

A sample configuration file is included. Of course none of you will be able to
use it since you won't have the same samples: just rip them out of some of the
many thousands of crappy mods out there (and delete the mod when you are done)

I recommend assigning a channel each type of sample: cymbals to one, bass drums
to another, snares to another, and toms to the last one.

If  you have any keys left over, you can load up useful samples such as crowds,
or  rapper phrazes like "get down", "get back up again", "in the city streets",
and  "till  the  night is over".  In fact, you could record your own number one
techno  hit  by  including  the right samples on your keypad...then release the
video with you standing there hitting keys on your Amiga keyboard....hmmm..well
as long as you wear a baseball cap on backwards and do lots of wierd signs with
your free hand..top of the charts for sure.

But I digress. Should you want to quit @{i}==---A-P-E-R-C-K-E-Y--->@{ui}, just
press Amiga-A (the sign of an AMOS program) and hit control-C.

Now load up some @{"recommended listening material" link "music"}, and get a
life! 

When  your  skills increase, you won't need any music to help you.  You will be
able to do fantastic solos that will amaze your friends at a warez party and be
sure to get you access to that Warez BBS.
@endnode

@node "cumming"
The next version of @{i}==---A-P-E-R-C-K-E-Y--->@{ui}, should there be one,
will be written in C instead on AMOS, and will be totally system friendly.
This has already been started, but I don't have time at  the moment, so I just
wrote this 10 liner in AMOS to show you what to look forward to. Features to
look forward to include:

friendly GUI (MUI??) interface
+ IFF sample support
+ Programmable keys
+ Session recording so you can save those brilliant improvisations
+ loop mode (like a real drum machine)
+ fills etc
etc.

If you want this version to see the light of day, please lobby PWS on
comp.sys.amiga.* :)
@endnode

@node "note"
@{i}==---A-P-E-R-C-K-E-Y--->@{ui} requires:

Amiga computer... (use PWSInfo to find out :)
KS2.04+
1+Meg Fast RAM
1+Meg Chip RAM
Harddisk (with a collection of suitable samples somewhere on it)
Keypad (sucked in A600's: and u thought u'd never need it eh!)

If @{i}==---A-P-E-R-C-K-E-Y--->@{ui} works on an Amiga with less than the above,
then count yourself lucky. I don't support lame machines.
@endnode

@node "aboutPWS"
@{b}@{u}About PWS.@{ub}@{uu}

@{" Press Release 30/9/93 " Link "moreinfo"}

Be sure to catch our many other quality software releases:

@{b}PWSInfo@{ub}     Amiga diagnostic/benchmark program
@{b}GreatChess@{ub}  The definitive computerized chess game
@{b}PWSHiTerm@{ub}   High speed terminal program.
@{b}SoftAGA@{ub}     gave us a few chuckles did that one! ** It really works :) **
@{b}PWSMods@{ub}     Various atonal mods to make your ears bleed.

Soon to be inflicted upon the public:

PWSDemo     yes our first ---++++===MeGa===+++--- Demo will be released some
            time in the next few months...

Want  to  join in the fun at PWS?  We are establishing PWS(M)C ...the Piss Weak
Software  (Mega)  Consortium:   an  international  group  of  fans, supporters,
contributors  and  critics  of  PWS  with  the  greater  aim of increasing user
awareness  and  supporting higher standards of programming on the Amiga.  As an
introductory  offer,  new  members receive the PWS Gold Collection:  the entire
PWS  Collection  on  disk  with  a  special preface written by the PWS founding
members,  and even some rare, never before published PWS stuff, including mods,
programming  outtakes,  and  other material not deemed suitable for general PWS
distribution.

l8r then dudez!

Don't forget to @{" Kall our board " link "bbs"}!! 

@endnode

@node "moreinfo"
Greetings Fellow Lamerz!

    This  is  my  first public statement on behalf of PWS (Piss Weak Software).
PWS is an organisation intended to raise the general standard of programming on
the  Amiga.   Unfortunately, it seems that we have done our work too well...and
have  been  left  behind ourselves.  Well, except for the demo coders..which is
our next major target area.  But more on that l8r (dudez).
    Anyway,  don't  think  that  this  means  we will be giving up bringing you
quality Amiga utilities:  already major revisions are being planned for SoftAGA
and  BBSFrazer.   In  addition,  another  couple  of  little  tools are nearing
completion that will shortly be infesting your drives.
    Be  advised however, that at the end of this year we shall unleash the most
aWeSuM  demo  ever  to  hit your screens.  We're talking way qool, elite coderz
only  here.   In  fact  only  hackerz  and  warez  dudez will b allowed 2 c it,
_that's_  how  eLiTe  we  r.   The  demo will include all the latest techo-shit
"music",  written  by  good  *programmers*,  and mind numbing, blindingly fast,
awesumly  orginal code, written by good musicians.  The demo will run on A500's
(no  fast  mem  please),  maybe A2000's, and also definitely A4000's !!!!  YES!
AGA  graphics!  A patch will also be available to make it run on the A1200 (but
only  after a month of us insisting it works on all machines).  Please, no hard
drives.   Also,  it  will  work  on the A3000, but only after all caches, burst
modes  have  been removed and you have booted into 1.2.  But the screen will be
corrupted (y didn't u just buy a A500 guyz?  So much simpler).
    Just  to  finish  up, a review of our releases to date.  Firstly there were
Great  Chess,  PWSHi-Term and PWSInfo.  A trio of gifts to the Amiga community.
These  have  not made an appearance on the international scene so if you want a
copy  you'll  have  to request them.  Then came the much applauded SoftAGA, and
the  brilliant  BBSFrazer.   Watch  out for the very upcoming BBSFrazer 2.0.1a.
This  would  already have made an appearance apart from a certain "recoverable"
RAM  drive  deciding  3.0  was too new to be supported just yet (just as well I
have STAT-ic column RAM eh?) The ear bleeding mods will be in the -*DeMo*-.
     ----           ---
@endnode

